{"title_page": "Lorenzo Dow", "text_new": "'''Lorenzo Dow''' (October 16, 1777{{spaced ndash}}February 2, 1834) was an eccentric itinerant [[Americans|American]] evangelist, said to have preached to more people than any other preacher of his era. He became an important figure and a popular writer. His autobiography at one time was the second best-selling book in the United States, exceeded only by the [[Bible]].\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn at [[Coventry, Connecticut]], to Humphrey Dow and Tabitha Parker Dow, Dow was a sickly child and was much troubled in his youth by \"religious speculations,\" but ultimately joined the [[Methodist]] faith. In 1796 he made an unsuccessful application for admission into the Connecticut conference; but two years later he was received, and in 1798\u2014despite the objections of his family\u2014was appointed to be a circuit preacher, on a probationary basis, to the Cambridge circuit in New York. During the year he was transferred to [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]], and afterward to [[Essex, Vermont]], but remained there only a brief time.<ref>Price, Richard Nye. [https://books.google.com/books?id=VaE9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Lorenzo and Peggy Dow.'']  ''Holston Methodism: From Its Origin to the Present Time, Volume 2.'' Publishing House of the M.E. Church, South, Smith & Lamar, 1912, pp.&nbsp;39\u201373.</ref>\n\n== Missionary travels ==\n[[File:Lorenzo Dow by Lossing-Barrett.jpg|thumb|Lorenzo Dow preaching, engraving by Lossing-Barrett, 1856]]\n\nDow made three visits to Ireland and England, in 1799, 1805 and 1818, and by his eccentric manners and attractive eloquence drew after him immense crowds.<ref>[[Benjamin Griffith Brawley]]. [http://docsouth.unc.edu/church/brawleyld/brawley.html Lorenzo Dow], ''The Journal of Negro History'', Volume 1, no. 3 (July 1916), 265-275.</ref> He took what he believed to be a divine call and crossed the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to preach as a missionary to the [[Catholic]]s of [[Ireland]], and thereafter was never connected officially with the ministry of the Methodist Church, though he remained essentially a Methodist in doctrine. He introduced camp meetings into England, and the controversy about them resulted in the organization of the [[Primitive Methodist Church|Primitive Methodist Society]].<ref>Farndale, W.E. ''The Secret of Mow Cop: A New appraisal of the Origins of Primitive Methodism''. Epworth Press, London. 1950. Page 28: \"Lorenzo Dow ... in 1807 ... preached at Hariseahead, Burslem, and Tunstall (Aug 16, 1818), where he met Hugh Bourne [one of the founders of the English Priimitive Methodists]\".</ref>\n\nIn 1802 he preached in the [[Albany, New York|Albany]] region of [[New York (state)|New York]], against [[atheism]], [[deism]], [[Calvinism]] and [[Universalism]]. He passed the years 1803 and 1804 in what was then the [[Mississippi Territory]] (present day states of [[Mississippi]] and [[Alabama]]), delivering the first [[Protestant]] sermon within the bounds of those future states. Just south of Mansfield, Georgia, on State Route 11, is a large rock on which is a plaque, placed by the [[Daughters of the American Revolution]]. It states that on that rock, in 1803, Dow preached the first \"Gospel sermon\" in Jasper County. In 1807 he extended his labors into [[Louisiana Territory]].<ref>Henry Sheets. [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=QBocAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9lAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=6910%2C4570803 Lorenzo and Peggy Dow: A Sketch of the Celebrated Lorenzo Dow and his Wife, Peggy,] ''The Dispatch'', January 18, 1905.</ref>\n\nDow's enthusiasm sustained him through the incessant labors of more than 30 years, during which he preached in almost all parts of the United States. His later efforts were directed chiefly against the [[Jesuit]]s; indeed he was in general a vigorous opponent of [[Roman Catholic]]ism.\n\nEverywhere, in America and Britain, he attracted great crowds to hear and see him, and he was often persecuted as well as admired. Because the churches were closed to him, Lorenzo Dow preached in town halls, farmers' barns, and even in open fields. He would preach anyplace where he could assemble a crowd. He preached to Methodists, Baptists, Quakers, Catholics, and atheists alike. He liked to appear unexpectedly at public events, announcing in a loud voice that exactly one year from today, Lorenzo Dow would preach on this spot. He never disappointed his audiences; he always appeared exactly 365 days later at the appointed place, usually met by huge crowds.\n\nDow's public speaking mannerisms were like nothing ever seen before among the typically conservative church goers of the time. He shouted, he screamed, he cried, he begged, he flattered, he insulted, he challenged people and their beliefs. He told stories and made jokes. It is recorded that Lorenzo Dow often preached before open-air assemblies of 10,000 people or more and held the audiences spellbound.\n\n== Traveling preacher ==\n[[File:Peggy Dow, aged 35 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|Peggy Dow, aged 35]]\nDow's fame spread, and so did his travels. He traveled on foot and occasionally on horseback (when someone would donate a horse) sometimes accompanied by his wife, Peggy Dow throughout what was then the United States. His journeys took him to Canada, England and Ireland, and once to the West Indies. He was usually well-received although there were exceptions. A fierce [[Abolitionism in the United States|abolitionist]], Dow's sermons were often unpopular in the southern United States, and he frequently was threatened with personal violence. He sometimes was forcibly ejected from towns, pelted with stones, eggs, and rotten vegetables as it happened in Jacksonborough, Georgia around 1820.<ref>[http://georgiamysteries.blogspot.com/2008/04/jacksonborough-curse.html?m=1], ''Touring the Backroads of North and South Georgia''</ref> That never stopped him; he simply walked to the next town and gave the same sermon again.\n\nLorenzo Dow was personally unkempt. He did not practice personal hygiene and his long hair and beard were described as \"never having met a comb.\" He usually owned one set of clothes: those that were on his back. When those clothes became so badly worn and full of holes that they were no longer capable of covering him, some person in the audience usually would donate a replacement. The donated clothes often were not the correct size for his skinny body. When he traveled, he carried no luggage other than a box of Bibles to be given away. Throughout most of his life, what little money he ever collected was either given away to the poor or used to purchase Bibles. In his later years, he did accumulate a bit of money from the sales of his autobiography and religious writings. His singularities of manner and of dress excited prejudices against him, and counteracted the effect of his eloquence. Nevertheless, he is said to have preached to more persons than any man of his time.<ref>{{cite Appletons'|title=DOW, Lorenzo |volume=2 |year=1888 |page=218|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o6coAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA218}}</ref>\n\nHe died in [[Georgetown, Washington, D.C.|Georgetown,]] in 1834 after illness being cared about by his friend George Haller, and had asked before passing away to use his old greatcoat as his winding sheet. He was placed to rest at [[Holmead's Burying Ground]].<ref>{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Ridgely|first=Helen West|title=Historic Graves of Maryland and the District of Columbia, With the Appearing on the Tombstones in Most of the Counties of the State and in Washington and Georgetown|location=New York|publisher=Grafton Press|date=1908|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=81odAAAAMAAJ&dq=Anthony%20Holmead%20cemetery&pg=PA258#v=onepage&q=Anthony%20Holmead%20cemetery&f=false}}</ref> A headstone with an [[epitaph]] that he personally selected was placed on his grave:\n{{quote|A Christian is the highest style of man;<br>\nHe is a slave to no sect, takes no private road,<br>\nBut looks through nature up to nature's God.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=TqpJAQAAMAAJ&lpg=PA416&dq=Peggy%20Dow%20eccentric&pg=PA416#v=onepage&q&f=false The New England Magazine, Volume 26], p. 416.</ref>}}\n\nIn 1887, when old Holmead's cemetery was about to be abolished, [[William Wilson Corcoran]] donated money and Dow was disinterred and moved to [[Oak Hill Cemetery (Washington, D.C.)|Oak Hill Cemetery]], near Georgetown.<ref name=\"Chapin\">{{cite book|ref=harv|last=Chapin|first=Elizabeth Moore|title=American Court Gossip; or, Life at the National Capitol|location=Marshalltown, Ia.|publisher=Chapin & Hartwell Bros.|date=1887|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Vmjlg_J62fkC&dq=%22Parrot's%20Woods%22&pg=PA258#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>\n\n== Remembrance ==\nHis influence and popularity during his life led to many children of the early 19th century, especially on the [[American frontier]], to be named after him.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=z_wTAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA412#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Clermont County\"] ''Historical Collections of Ohio: An Encyclopedia of the State. Volume 1.'' Columbus: H. Howe & Son, 1889, pp.&nbsp;412\u2013413, 418. Page 418 contains an engraving of an 1821 portrait of Dow, and a drawing of Dow preaching in New Haven, Connecticut in 1832.</ref> In the 1818 Washington almanac, there is a humorous anecdote about Lorenzo Dow saving a woman's infidelity by pretending to raise the devil (the woman's paramour, who was hiding in a barrel, which Dow set on fire).<ref>[http://www.worldcat.org/title/washington-almanac-for-the-year-of-our-lord-1818/oclc/15440901&referer=brief_results ''The Washington Almanac for the year of our Lord 1818 ...\"] Sharp, J. (1817). The Washington almanac, for the year of our Lord 1818. Baltimore [Md.]: Cushing & Jewett.</ref> His autobiography became a bestseller and the [[1850 U.S. Census]] counts Lorenzo as one of the most popular first names in America.<ref>Micklethwait, John, and Adrian Wooldridge. [https://books.google.com/books?id=jlNOHAr46HEC&pg=PA69&lpg=PA69&dq=lorenzo+name+popularity+1850+census&source=bl&ots=hBcynanRal&sig=8Y6PAM8sf1l07Rq2OdU3JUywWhE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiKxZTE4K3LAhVMOT4KHTi9AAAQ6AEIKTAD#v=onepage&q&f=false ''God Is Back: How the Global Revival of Faith Is Changing the World.''] New York: Penguin Press, 2009, p. 69-70.</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nHis wife, Peggy Dow (1780\u20131820), was almost as eccentric as her husband.<ref>Gilbert, Jesse S. [https://books.google.com/books?id=Lb8QAAAAIAAJ&lpg=PA411&ots=jRC6C84bst&dq=Peggy%20Dow%20eccentric&pg=PA411#v=onepage&q&f=false Lorenzo and Peggy Dow], ''Methodist Magazine and Review,'' Volume 59.</ref> She published her journal, entitled ''Vicissitudes in the Wilderness'' (1833).<ref>Dow, Peggy. ''Vicissitudes in the Wilderness: Exemplified in the Journal of Peggy Dow.'' Norwich, Conn: Printed by W. Faulkner, 1833.</ref>\n\n== Selected works ==\n* ''Polemical Works'' (1814)\n* ''The Stranger in Charleston, or the Trial and Confession of Lorenzo Dow'' (1822)\n* ''A Short Account of a Long Travel; with Beauties of Wesley'' (1823)\n* ''History of a Cosmopolite; or the Four Volumes of the Rev. Lorenzo Dow's Journal, concentrated in One, containing his Experience and Travels from Childhood to 1814'' (1814; many later editions); this volume also contains \"All the Polemical Works of Lorenzo.\" The edition of 1854 was entitled ''The Dealings of God, Man, and the Devil as exemplified in the Life, Experience and Travels of Lorenzo Dow''.,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=fz4XAAAAYAAJ ''History of a Cosmopolite, 1814 1st edn.'']</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=SYNllIx56rUC ''History of a Cosmopolite, 1848 5th edn.'']</ref><ref>[https://archive.org/details/historyofcosmopo00dowuoft ''History of a Cosmopolite, 1858 edn.'']</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{Appletons'|title=Dow, Lorenzo |volume=2 |year=1888|page=218 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o6coAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA218}}\n* {{NIE|wstitle=Dow, Lorenzo}}\n* {{EB1911|wstitle=Dow, Lorenzo}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n*Dow, Lorenzo. [https://archive.org/stream/eccentricpreacher00dowl#page/n7/mode/2up ''The Eccentric Preacher: Or, a Sketch of the Life of the Celebrated Lorenzo Dow, Abridged from His Journal; and Containing the Most Interesting Facts in His Experience.''] Lowell: E.A. Rice & Co, 1841.\n*Dow, Peggy. [https://archive.org/stream/vicissitudesinwi00dowp#page/n5/mode/2up ''Vicissitudes in the Wilderness: Exemplified in the Journal of Peggy Dow.''] Norwich, Conn: Printed by W. Faulkner, 1833.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Internet Archive author|sname=Dow, Lorenzo}}\n* Montgomery, Sue. [http://www.dentongenealogy.org/Lorenzo%20Dow.htm Lorenzo Dow], ''Denton Family Genealogy''.\n* [http://georgiainfo.galileo.usg.edu/topics/historical_markers/county/franklin/the-franklin-springs The Franklin Springs] historical marker\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dow, Lorenzo}}\n[[Category:1777 births]]\n[[Category:1834 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Coventry, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:American abolitionists]]\n[[Category:American theologians]]\n[[Category:American Methodist clergy]]\n[[Category:Burials at Oak Hill Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Critics of the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Burials at Holmead's Burying Ground]]tee hee\n", "text_old": "'''Lorenzo Dow''' (October 16, 1777{{spaced ndash}}February 2, 1834) was an eccentric itinerant [[Americans|American]] evangelist, said to have preached to more people than any other preacher of his era. He became an important figure and a popular writer. His autobiography at one time was the second best-selling book in the United States, exceeded only by the [[Bible]].\n\n== Early life ==\nBorn at [[Coventry, Connecticut]], to Humphrey Dow and Tabitha Parker Dow, Dow was a sickly child and was much troubled in his youth by \"religious speculations,\" but ultimately joined the [[Methodist]] faith. In 1796 he made an unsuccessful application for admission into the Connecticut conference; but two years later he was received, and in 1798\u2014despite the objections of his family\u2014was appointed to be a circuit preacher, on a probationary basis, to the Cambridge circuit in New York. During the year he was transferred to [[Pittsfield, Massachusetts]], and afterward to [[Essex, Vermont]], but remained there only a brief time.<ref>Price, Richard Nye. [https://books.google.com/books?id=VaE9AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA39#v=onepage&q&f=false ''Lorenzo and Peggy Dow.'']  ''Holston Methodism: From Its Origin to the Present Time, Volume 2.'' Publishing House of the M.E. Church, South, Smith & Lamar, 1912, pp.&nbsp;39\u201373.</ref>\n\n== Missionary travels ==\n[[File:Lorenzo Dow by Lossing-Barrett.jpg|thumb|Lorenzo Dow preaching, engraving by Lossing-Barrett, 1856]]\n\nDow made three visits to Ireland and England, in 1799, 1805 and 1818, and by his eccentric manners and attractive eloquence drew after him immense crowds.<ref>[[Benjamin Griffith Brawley]]. [http://docsouth.unc.edu/church/brawleyld/brawley.html Lorenzo Dow], ''The Journal of Negro History'', Volume 1, no. 3 (July 1916), 265-275.</ref> He took what he believed to be a divine call and crossed the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to preach as a missionary to the [[Catholic]]s of [[Ireland]], and thereafter was never connected officially with the ministry of the Methodist Church, though he remained essentially a Methodist in doctrine. He introduced camp meetings into England, and the controversy about them resulted in the organization of the [[Primitive Methodist Church|Primitive Methodist Society]].<ref>Farndale, W.E. ''The Secret of Mow Cop: A New appraisal of the Origins of Primitive Methodism''. Epworth Press, London. 1950. Page 28: \"Lorenzo Dow ... in 1807 ... preached at Hariseahead, Burslem, and Tunstall (Aug 16, 1818), where he met Hugh Bourne [one of the founders of the English Priimitive Methodists]\".</ref>\n\nIn 1802 he preached in the [[Albany, New York|Albany]] region of [[New York (state)|